      "id": "74e073ff-510f-4cd2-995c-9d38f3c037bf",
      "timestamp": "2026-06-22T18:44:00.096275+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "I now have a thorough picture of the whole system. Here's what I found:\n\n---\n\n## Current state\n\nThe `AIUsage` dataclass already has `cache_read_tokens` and `cache_write_tokens` fields, and `_update_usage()` on the base class already accepts both. The infrastructure is fully in place \u2014 only Anthropic actually populates those fields.\n\n---\n\n## What each backend can realistically provide\n\n### OpenAI / xAI / vLLM / Mistral / DeepSeek / Z.ai (OpenAI-compatible `_handle_usage`)\nThese all receive a `usage` dict and call `_update_usage` with only the three basic fields. OpenAI **does** expose a `cached_tokens` field \u2014 it appears in:\n\n```json\n\"usage\": {\n  \"prompt_tokens\": 100,\n  \"completion_tokens\": 50,\n  \"total_tokens\": 150,\n  \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\n    \"cached_tokens\": 30\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSo for **OpenAI**, `cached_tokens` is a **cache read** count, nested under `prompt_tokens_details`. **xAI (Grok)** uses the same OpenAI-compatible format and also exposes `cached_tokens` in `prompt_tokens_details`. **vLLM** may or may not expose it depending on the model/version \u2014 it's OpenAI-compatible so the field would be in the same place if present. **Mistral** and **Z.ai** don't appear to expose cache read stats in their usage responses.\n\n### DeepSeek\nDeepSeek's usage response includes a `prompt_cache_hit_tokens` field (and `prompt_cache_miss_tokens`) directly in the usage object \u2014 no nesting:\n\n```json\n\"usage\": {\n  \"prompt_tokens\": 100,\n  \"completion_tokens\": 50,\n  \"total_tokens\": 150,\n  \"prompt_cache_hit_tokens\": 30,\n  \"prompt_cache_miss_tokens\": 70\n}\n```\n\n### Google (Gemini)\nGoogle uses `usageMetadata` with different field names. There is a `cachedContentTokenCount` field for tokens served from the **explicit context cache** (a separate paid API feature). However, the implicit prompt caching (automatic, like Anthropic's) doesn't seem to be reported in the streaming `usageMetadata` in the same way. So this one is the least clear-cut.\n\n### Ollama\nOllama runs local models and doesn't have a concept of a shared prompt cache in the same way \u2014 it does have a KV cache but doesn't report cache hits in its `done` response. This one is effectively N/A.\n\n---\n\n## Summary table\n\n| Backend | Cache read field | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Anthropic** | \u2705 `cache_read_input_tokens` in `usage` | Already implemented |\n| **OpenAI** | \u2705 `usage.prompt_tokens_details.cached_tokens` | Ready to add |\n| **xAI** | \u2705 Same as OpenAI | Ready to add |\n| **DeepSeek** | \u2705 `usage.prompt_cache_hit_tokens` | Ready to add |\n| **vLLM** | \u26a0\ufe0f `usage.prompt_tokens_details.cached_tokens` | Present if model/version supports it; safe to add with `get()` defaulting to 0 |\n| **Mistral** | \u274c Not exposed | Nothing to do |\n| **Z.ai** | \u274c Not reliably exposed | Nothing to do |\n| **Google** | \u26a0\ufe0f `usageMetadata.cachedContentTokenCount` | Only counts explicit context cache, not automatic caching |\n| **Ollama** | \u274c Local KV cache, not reported | Nothing to do |\n\nThe changes needed are purely in `_handle_usage()` in each relevant stream response handler \u2014 a few extra `.get()` calls. Want me to go ahead and implement this?",
